---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import Breadcrumbs from '../../components/Breadcrumbs.astro';
---
<Base
  title="Policies — OpenXiv"
  description="OpenXiv repository policies: code of conduct, submission, metadata, items, preservation, takedown, jurisdictional restrictions. Plain English."
>
  <main class="container-narrow">
    <Breadcrumbs items={[{ name: 'Home', url: '/' }, { name: 'Policies', url: '/policies' }]} />
    <h1 class="title-serif">Policies</h1>
    <p class="muted">
      Last updated 2026-05-19. The documents below describe how
      OpenXiv handles submissions, metadata, content licensing,
      long-term preservation, takedown and withdrawal requests,
      and jurisdictional restrictions. Each one is written in
      plain English, not legalese; when something is uncertain we
      say so.
    </p>

    <section class="policy-list">
      <article class="card policy-card">
        <h2><a href="/policies/code-of-conduct">Code of conduct</a></h2>
        <p class="body-serif">
          Expectations for authors, endorsers, readers, and
          moderators. Refuse the work, not the author. Public
          refusal packets. Sanctions ladder from "return for
          revision" to (rare) account suspension.
        </p>
      </article>

      <article class="card policy-card">
        <h2><a href="/policies/submission">Submission policy</a></h2>
        <p class="body-serif">
          Who may submit, what we accept, what we refuse, how AI use is
          disclosed, how rejections work. PDF-only uploads are blocked;
          source archives are required.
        </p>
      </article>

      <article class="card policy-card">
        <h2><a href="/policies/metadata">Metadata policy</a></h2>
        <p class="body-serif">
          Bibliographic data is CC0 — reuse freely. Lists the standards
          we emit (Dublin Core via OAI-PMH, Crossref schema, Google
          Scholar tags, JSON-LD). How corrections propagate.
        </p>
      </article>

      <article class="card policy-card">
        <h2><a href="/policies/items">Content / item policy</a></h2>
        <p class="body-serif">
          Authors retain copyright. Pick a license at submit (CC-BY-4.0
          default). No paywalls, no embargoes. Modifications via new
          versions, never silent edits.
        </p>
      </article>

      <article class="card policy-card">
        <h2><a href="/policies/preservation">Preservation policy</a></h2>
        <p class="body-serif">
          DOIs through Crossref, replicated storage, daily snapshots,
          documented handoff plan to Zenodo. Honest about what a young
          single-operator project can promise.
        </p>
      </article>

      <article class="card policy-card">
        <h2><a href="/policies/takedown">Takedown / withdrawal policy</a></h2>
        <p class="body-serif">
          Authors can withdraw; the record stays accessible with a
          "Withdrawn" badge. Third-party copyright complaints use
          DMCA. Misconduct outcomes are public.
        </p>
      </article>

      <article class="card policy-card">
        <h2><a href="/policies/jurisdictional-restrictions">Jurisdictional restrictions</a></h2>
        <p class="body-serif">
          If a national authority issues a binding legal demand,
          we may geo-restrict an item for viewers in that
          jurisdiction. Reactive, documented on the
          <a href="/transparency">transparency report</a>,
          reversible. Content is never deleted, the DOI continues
          to resolve, and the author keeps all rights.
        </p>
      </article>
    </section>

    <p class="muted" style="margin-top: 32px;">
      Related: <a href="/about">About</a> · <a href="/terms">Submission terms</a>
      · <a href="/privacy">Privacy</a> · <a href="/dmca">DMCA intake</a>
      · <a href="/transparency">Transparency report</a>.
    </p>
  </main>
</Base>

<style>
  .policy-list { display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 12px; margin-top: 20px; }
  .policy-card { padding: 16px 18px; }
  .policy-card h2 {
    margin: 0 0 6px;
    font-family: var(--font-serif);
    font-size: 18px;
  }
  .policy-card h2 a { color: inherit; }
  .policy-card p { margin: 0; font-size: 14.5px; line-height: 1.5; }
</style>
